<td xpos="16" content="" csheight="335" align="left" height="312" valign="top" width="976"><font size="+1"><b>California Forest Fire Lookout sites, 506 active and abandoned sites listed. Table 2, Revised March 23, 2021.</b></font>
<p><font size="+1">Key to column headings: <b>ID</b> - A numerical count, <b>County</b> - The county the Lookout is in, <b>Topo Map</b> - The name of the 7.5 minute topographic map the Lookout is on, <b>Lookout Name</b> - Name of active Lookout or inactive site, <b>LO</b> - Status of standing Lookout (see below), <b>NHLR -</b> A entry indicates the lookout is on the National Historic Lookout Register. The registration number is shown. <b>Prom </b>- The prominence value in feet, <b>EL, ft</b>. - Elevation in feet of the Lookout,<b> EL</b>
- How elevation is determined. BM = benchmark survey disk nearby. Spot
= spot elevation shown on the map. Inter. = No elevation shown so
interpreted from contours. <b>Forest </b>- Name of National Forest Lookout is in, <b>Park or Other</b> - Other Land status, <b>BM Name</b> - The name of the benchmark disk near the Lookout, <b>PID</b> - The unique number or <u>P</u>osition <u>Id</u>entifier given by the USGS to each benchmark, <b>YR</b> - Year the benchmark disk was first placed, <b>LO BM </b>- A listing for the Lookout building itself. (This will give the most accurate coordinates for the building.)</font></p>
<p><font size="+1"><b>Lookout Status Codes:</b>
A = structure in good condition, capable of being staffed. B =
Dilapidated and needs work, but standing. C = Badly damaged or falling
down. AS = usually staffed by Forest Service or CDF. AV = staffed by
volunteers. AR = A rental Lookout. A (LO site) is where the building
has been removed and there may be no evidence remaining, or it's status
may be unknown.</font></p>
